column4: judgment as a matter of law ( jmol ) is a motion made by a party , during trial , claiming the opposing party has insufficient evidence to reasonably support its case .

column4: jmol is also known as a directed verdict , which it has replaced in american federal courts .

column3: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column4: in united states federal courts , jmol is a creation of federal rules of civil procedure rule 50 .

column3: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column4: jmol is decided by the standard of whether a reasonable jury could find in favor of the party opposing the jmol motion .

column3: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column4: if there is no evidence to support a reasonable conclusion for the opposing party , judgment is entered by the court and the case is over .

column3: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column4: if there is sufficient evidence to make a reasonable conclusion in favor of the opposing party , but there is equally strong evidence to support an opposite conclusion , the party with the burden of persuasion fails .

column3: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column4: timing is very important in making a motion for jmol ; the motion can only be made once the opposing party has presented its case .

column3: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column4: in civil cases , the plaintiff presents her case , then the defendant presents his/her case , then the plaintiff may present a rebuttal .

column3: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column4: so , once the plaintiff has presented his/her case , the defendant may move for jmol , but the plaintiff may not .

column3: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column4: once the defendant has finished presenting his/her case , the plaintiff may move for jmol , and so may the defendant .

column3: what does judgment as a matter of law mean

column3: what does judgment as a matter of law mean

column3: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column4: this procedural quirk is necessary because it is considered a violation of the 7th amendment for a judge to overturn a jury verdict .

column3: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column4: instead , the judge is said in a j.n.o.v. to be reexamining not the verdict , but his previous rejection of jmol .
